The paper focuses on the human and social aspects of software engineering, specifically on the impact of affects (emotions and moods) on software development performance. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) category. Additionally, the paper draws on literature from psychology and discusses the psychology of programming, indicating that it could also fit into the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) category. The paper also mentions software development tasks and productivity, suggesting that it could belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) category. The mixed method approach used in the study could also place it in the Cybernetics (cs.CY) category. Finally, the paper discusses interventions for enhancing affects on the job, which could potentially place it in the Computation and Language (cs.CL) category.
